    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let me try to explain it in a more straightforward way.\n\nQuantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become correlated in such a way that the state of one particle is dependent on the state of the other, even when they are separated by large distances. When you measure the state of one particle, it instantly affects the state of the other entangled particle, regardless of the distance between them.\n\nThink of it like a game of \"ping-pong\" between the particles. When you measure the state of one particle, it's like hitting a ball that instantly bounces back to the other particle, affecting its state. This happens even if the particles are separated by billions of kilometers, which is much faster than the speed of light.\n\nThe key point is that this effect happens instantaneously, which is difficult to understand using classical notions of space and time. It's a fundamental aspect of quantum mechanics that challenges our intuition about the nature of reality.\n\nNow, to clarify, classical correlation is a different concept. In classical physics, two particles can be correlated in such a way that measuring the state of one particle gives you information about the state of the other particle. However,",
      "source": "target",
